"## Chapter 16 — What Comes Next

Chapter 15 said *go build something.* This chapter says what to do the morning after.

You have a REPL that starts. You have a cart directory that behaves like a folder of little programs. You have a reference file that is the language. That's enough to make a thing. Now — how do other people see it?

### The bench

Before you show anything to anyone else, sit with it on the bench. The bench is just running the cart on your own machine and watching. Not testing. Not proving. Watching. Does the blossom draw where you thought? Does the sound arrive when you wanted? Does the number on screen match the number in your head?

The bench catches the bug that unit tests never see: the *invisible* bug, where the code returns `ok` but nothing paints. Sakura Scheme has a rule about this — nothing counts as done until you saw it on your device. Not on CI. Not in a log line. On the screen you're holding.

### The share

Once the bench passes, share it. The smallest share is one link, one line. `sakura publish my-cart` gives you a URL. The URL renders. A friend opens it on their phone. They don't install anything.

That's the whole share. No dependency file. No lock file. No `npm install`. The cart is a small text file that runs the same way on your machine and on the friend's phone because the reference is the language, and the language is everywhere.

### The community

If the thing you built is good enough that strangers want it, they'll say so. If it's off, they'll say that too. Both are useful. The community around Sakura Scheme is small — small enough that a real person reads issues, small enough that an author still knows every cart by name. Take that seriously. Answer the person who reported the bug. Thank the person who fixed a typo. When you author your own dialect, publish the `dialect.slat` file so the next person can read what you changed and why.

### Being paid

Sakura is a language and a shop at the same time. If your cart makes money, some verbs charge — the paid ones are the ones that reach out to the world (marketplace listings, external APIs). The free ones (drawing, math, list work) never charge. You can build almost anything for free. The moment a verb costs a coin, you'll see the coin in the ledger.

That's the whole trick. Free at rest, paid at the wire. No paywall in front of a REPL. No trial that expires while you're in the middle of a thought.

### The next book

This book got you standing. The next books are shaped like moves.

- *Book of Motion* — how to make things move on the screen.
- *Book of Music* — how to make sound that a person wants to hear.
- *Book of Money* — the coin, honestly.
- *Book of Marionette* — the sixteen little characters and how they behave.

Pick one. Read it the same way — a chapter a night, a cart per chapter. When you finish, the next kid who opens Sakura Scheme is standing on your work.

— Jesse

*✿*
")
